<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-217-046 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 368 641</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 25 1991 v25 n8 p52(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Niagara Mohawk looks to tap the power of networking. (NiagaraMohawk Power Corp. 'downsizing' from mainframes to microcomputernetworks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nash, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Niagara Mohawk Power Corp is moving some of its employees ontomicrocomputer LANs and away from mainframes in an effort toincrease database access and increase the efficiency of workgroups.andP;  Officials at Niagara Mohawk expect that downloadingspecialized data from a mainframe to a LAN will allow 10 to 25percent faster access.andP;  The utility company stores its data on anIBM 3090 Model 400S mainframe which a typical four-persondepartment accesses for a total of 14 hours per day.andP;  Switchingusers to networked microcomputers would save the company anaverage of $2,000 per employee annually.andP;  Niagara Mohawk does notintend to abandon its mainframe entirely, citing the advantages ofcentral control, backup, disaster recovery, security and support.andO;It hopes to have at least one work group using a transferredfixed-asset tracking application by Mar 1991.andP;  Ninety to 100systems applications currently reside on the 3090.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Niagara Mohawk Power Corp. (Data processing).andO;Ticker:    NMK.andO;Topic:     Case StudyMainframe computersLocal Area NetworksSystem ConversionSystem Selection.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>